# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-glacier
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] Glacier is part of the Amazon Web Services suite of cloud computing services, and is designed for long-term storage of data that is infrequently accessed and for which standard retrieval latency times of 12 to 48 hours are acceptable.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] Base monthly storage costs are $0.00099/GB or about $1/TB (East Coast USA Prices).
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] This is substantially cheaper than the Simple Storage Service (S3) Standard tier with its nearly instant egress times.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] Amazon aims to move customers from on-premises tape backup drives to cloud-based backup.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] The storage technology used by Glacier, indeed for all of S3, is an Amazon trade secret.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] ZDNet says, that according to private e-mail, Glacier runs on "inexpensive commodity hardware components".
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] In 2012, ZDNet quoted a former Amazon employee as saying that Glacier is based on custom low-RPM hard drives attached to custom logic boards where only a percentage of a rack's drives can be spun at full speed at any one time.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] Similar technology is also used by Facebook.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] There is some belief among users that the underlying hardware used for Glacier storage is tape-based, because Amazon has positioned Glacier as a direct competitor to tape backup services both on-premises and cloud-based.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] This is seems supported by the fact that Glacier has a standard long archive retrieval of up to 12 hours, called "thawing", and a pricing model that discourages frequent data retrieval (the effect of batching requests to reduce wear on mechanical equipment).
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] Glacier has at least four costs associated.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] The following prices reflect East Coast USA as of 2026 in USD, and is representative of how pricing is segmented into categories and their relative differences.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] Other regions may have different prices.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] Standard is 0.02 per GB (12 hour guarantee).
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] An egress (download) fee of 0.09 per GB.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] The prices for monthly storage have dropped over time: when Glacier launched in 2012, the storage charge was set to 1 cent per gigabyte per month.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] This was reduced to 0.7 cents in September 2015 and to 0.4 cents in December 2016.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] Glacier previously charged for retrievals based on *peak* monthly retrieval rate, meaning that (ignoring the free tier) if you downloaded four gigabytes in four hours, it would cost the same as if you downloaded 720 gigabytes in 720 hours, in a 30-day month.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] This made it cheaper to spread out data retrievals over a long period of time, but failing to do so could result in a surprisingly large bill.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] In one case, a user stored 15 GB of data in Glacier, retrieved 693 MB for testing, and ended up being charged for 126 GB due to retrieval rate calculation.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] This pricing policy was widely regarded as a "time bomb" set to go off on retrieval.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] In 2016, AWS revised their retrieval pricing model.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] The new model bases the retrieval fee on the number of gigabytes retrieved.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] This can amount to a 99% price cut for users who perform only one Glacier retrieval in a month.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] At the same time, AWS introduced new methods of retrieval that take different amounts of time.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] An *expedited* retrieval costs one cent per request and three cents per gigabyte, and can retrieve data in one to five minutes.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] A *standard* retrieval costs five cents per thousand requests and one cent per gigabyte, and takes three to five hours.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] A *bulk* retrieval costs 2.5 cents per thousand requests and 0.25 cents per gigabyte, and takes seven to twelve hours.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] AWS also introduced *provisioned capacity* for expedited retrievals, each unit of which costs $100 per month and guarantees at least three expedited retrievals every five minutes, and up to 150 MB/s of retrieval bandwidth.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] Without provisioned capacity, expedited retrievals are done on a capacity available basis.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] Data deleted from Glacier less than 180 days after being stored incurs a charge equal to the cost of storage for the remainder of the 180 days.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] In effect, the user pays for 180 days minimum.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] This move was designed to discourage the service's use in cases where Amazon's other storage offerings (e.g.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] S3) are more appropriate for real-time access.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] After 180 days, deletion from Glacier has no penalty.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] Retrieving data from Glacier is a two-step process.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] The first step is to retrieve the data into a staging area, where it stays for 24 hours.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] The second step is to download the data from the staging area, which incurs bandwidth charges.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] In 2019, Glacier migrated from the old "Vault" model to a storage class in the S3 product line.
[src:aws-glacier/amazon-glacier] This made it easier to access and manage through standard S3 APIs and tools.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] The concept of data management emerged alongside the evolution of computing technology.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] In the 1950s, as computers became more prevalent, organizations began to grapple with the challenge of organizing and storing data efficiently.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Early methods relied on punch cards and manual sorting, which were labor-intensive and prone to errors.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] The introduction of database management systems in the 1970s marked a significant milestone, enabling structured storage and retrieval of data.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] By the 1980s, relational database models revolutionized data management, emphasizing the importance of data as an asset and fostering a data-centric mindset in business.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] This era also saw the rise of data governance practices, which prioritized the organization and regulation of data to ensure quality and compliance.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Over time, advancements in technology, such as cloud computing and big data analytics, have further refined data management, making it a cornerstone of modern business operations.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] As of 2025, data management encompasses a wide range of practices, from data storage and security to analytics and decision-making, reflecting its critical role in driving innovation and efficiency across industries.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] The Data Management Body of Knowledge, DMBoK, developed by the Data Management Association, DAMA, outlines key knowledge areas that serve as the foundation for modern data management practices, suggesting a framework for organizations to manage data as a strategic asset.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Data governance refers to the policies, procedures, and standards that ensure data is managed consistently and responsibly across an organization.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] In enterprise contexts, governance involves aligning stakeholders across business units, defining data ownership, and quantifying the benefits of improved data quality.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Effective governance frameworks often include data stewardship roles, escalation protocols, and cross-functional oversight committees to maintain trust and accountability in data use.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Data architecture consist of models, policies, rules, and standards that govern which data is collected and how it is stored, arranged, integrated, and put to use in data systems and in organizations.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Data is usually one of several architecture domains that form the pillars of an enterprise architecture or solution architecture.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Data Architecture focuses on designing the overall structure of data systems.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] It ensures that data flows are efficient and that systems are scalable, adaptable, and aligned with business needs.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] This area centers on creating models that logically represent data relationships.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] It’s essential for both designing databases and ensuring that data is structured in a way that facilitates analysis and reporting.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Deals with the physical storage of data and its day-to-day management.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] This includes everything from traditional data centers to cloud-based storage solutions and ensuring efficient data processing.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Ensures that data from various sources can be seamlessly shared and combined across multiple systems, which is critical for comprehensive analytics and decision-making.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Focuses on managing unstructured data such as documents, multimedia, and other content, ensuring that it is stored, categorized, and easily retrievable.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Involves consolidating data into repositories that support analytics, reporting, and business insights.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] In computing, a data warehouse (DW or DWH), also known as an enterprise data warehouse (EDW), is a system used for reporting and data analysis and is a core component of business intelligence.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Data warehouses are central repositories of data integrated from disparate sources.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] They store current and historical data organized in a way that is optimized for data analysis, generation of reports, and developing insights across the integrated data.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] They are intended to be used by analysts and managers to help make organizational decisions.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Business intelligence (BI) consists of strategies, methodologies, and technologies used by enterprises for data analysis and management of business information to inform business strategies and business operations.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Common functions of BI technologies include reporting, online analytical processing, analytics, dashboard development, data mining, process mining, complex event processing, business performance management, benchmarking, text mining, predictive analytics, and prescriptive analytics.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] A data mart is a structure/access pattern specific to *data warehouse* environments.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] The data mart is a subset of the data warehouse that focuses on a specific business line, department, subject area, or team.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Whereas data warehouses have an enterprise-wide depth, the information in data marts pertains to a single department.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] In some deployments, each department or business unit is considered the *owner* of its data mart, including all the *hardware*, *software*, and *data*.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] This enables each department to isolate the use, manipulation, and development of their data.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] In other deployments where conformed dimensions are used, this business unit ownership will not hold true for shared dimensions like customer, product, etc.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Data analysis is the process of inspecting, cleansing, transforming, and modeling data with the goal of discovering useful information, informing conclusions, and supporting decision-making.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Data analysis has multiple facets and approaches, encompassing diverse techniques under a variety of names, and is used in different business, science, and social science domains.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] In today's business world, data analysis plays an important role in making decisions more scientific and helping businesses operate more effectively.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] It is widely used in fields such as business analytics, healthcare, and artificial intelligence to extract meaningful insights from data.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Data mining is the process of extracting and finding patterns in massive data sets involving methods at the intersection of machine learning, statistics, and database systems.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Data mining is an interdisciplinary subfield of computer science and statistics with an overall goal of extracting information (with intelligent methods) from a data set and transforming the information into a comprehensible structure for further use.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Data mining is the analysis step of the "knowledge discovery in databases" process, or KDD.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Aside from the raw analysis step, it also involves database and data management aspects, data pre-processing, model and inference considerations, interestingness metrics, complexity considerations, post-processing of discovered structures, visualization, and online updating.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] A data scientist is a professional who creates programming code and combines it with statistical knowledge to summarize data.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Manages data about data, including definitions, origin, and usage, to enhance the understanding and usability of the organization’s data assets.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Data quality is not only a technical concern but a strategic enabler of trust, compliance, and decision-making.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] High-quality data supports consistent reporting, regulatory adherence, and customer confidence.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Enterprise data management programs often define quality metrics such as precision, granularity, and timeliness, and link these to business outcomes.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Reference data comprises standardized codes and values for consistent interpretation across systems.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Master data management (MDM) governs and centralizes an organization’s critical data, ensuring a unified, reliable information source that supports effective decision-making and operational efficiency.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Data security refers to a comprehensive set of practices and technologies designed to protect digital information and systems from unauthorized access, use, disclosure, modification, or destruction.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] It encompasses encryption, access controls, monitoring, and risk assessments to maintain data integrity, confidentiality, and availability.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Data privacy involves safeguarding individuals’ personal information by ensuring its collection, storage, and use comply with consent, legal standards, and confidentiality principles.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] It emphasizes protecting sensitive data from misuse or unauthorized access while respecting users' rights.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] The distinction between data and derived value is illustrated by the "information ladder" or the DIKAR model.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] The "DIKAR" model stands for Data, Information, Knowledge, Action, and Result.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] It is a framework used to bridge the gap between raw data and actionable outcomes.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] The model emphasizes the transformation of data into information, which is then interpreted to create knowledge.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] This knowledge guides actions that lead to measurable results.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] DIKAR is widely applied in organizational strategies, helping businesses align their data management processes with decision-making and performance goals.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] By focusing on each stage, the model ensures that data is effectively utilized to drive informed decisions and achieve desired outcomes.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] It is particularly valuable in technology-driven environments.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] The "information ladder" illustrates the progression from data (raw facts) to information (processed data), knowledge (interpreted information), and ultimately wisdom (applied knowledge).
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Each step adds value and context, enabling better decision-making.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] It emphasizes the transformation of unstructured inputs into meaningful insights for practical use.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] In research, Data management refers to the systematic process of handling data throughout its lifecycle.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] This includes activities such as collecting, organizing, storing, analyzing, and sharing data to ensure its accuracy, accessibility, and security.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] A Data Management Plan (DMP) is a structured document that outlines how research data will be collected, organized, stored, shared, and preserved throughout and after a research project.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] It serves as a guide to ensure that data are handled responsibly, remain accessible, and are protected from loss or misuse.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Effective data management also involves creating a data management plan, DMP, addressing issues like ethical considerations, compliance with regulatory standards, and long-term preservation.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Proper management enhances research transparency, reproducibility, and the efficient use of resources, ultimately contributing to the credibility and impact of research findings.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] It is a critical practice across disciplines to ensure data integrity and usability both during and after a research project.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Big data refers to the collection and analyses of massive sets of data.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] While big data is a recent phenomenon, the requirement for data to aid decision-making traces back to the early 1970s with the emergence of decision support systems (DSS).
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] These systems can be considered as the initial iteration of data management for decision support.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Studies indicate that customer transactions account for a 40% increase in the data collected annually, which means that financial data has a considerable impact on business decisions.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Therefore, modern organizations are using big data analytics to identify 5 to 10 new data sources that can help them collect and analyze data for improved decision-making.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Jonsen (2013) explains that organizations using average analytics technologies are 20% more likely to gain higher returns compared to their competitors who have not introduced any analytics capabilities in their operations.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Also, IRI reported that the retail industry could experience an increase of more than $10 billion each year resulting from the implementation of modern analytics technologies.
[src:aws-glacier/data-management] Therefore, the following hypothesis can be proposed: Economic and financial outcomes can impact how organizations use data analytics tools.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] HSM may also be used where more robust storage is available for long-term archiving, but this is slow to access.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] This may be as simple as an off-site backup for recovery from disaster.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] HSM is a long-established concept, dating back to the beginnings of commercial data processing.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] The techniques used though have changed significantly as new technology becomes available, for both storage and for long-distance communication of large data sets.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] The scale of measures such as 'size' and 'access time' have changed dramatically.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] Despite this, many of the underlying concepts keep returning to favour years later, although at much larger or faster scales.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] In a typical HSM scenario, data which is frequently used are stored on warm storage device, such as solid-state disk (SSD).
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] Data that is infrequently accessed is, after some time *migrated* to a slower, high capacity cold storage tier.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] If a user does access data which is on the cold storage tier, it is automatically moved back to warm storage.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] The advantage is that the total amount of stored data can be much larger than the capacity of the warm storage device, but since only rarely used files are on cold storage, most users will usually not notice any slowdown.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] In practice, HSM is typically performed by dedicated software, such as IBM Tivoli Storage Manager, or Oracle's SAM-QFS.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] The deletion of files from a higher level of the hierarchy (e.g. magnetic disk) after they have been moved to a lower level (e.g. optical media) is sometimes called **file grooming**.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] Hierarchical Storage Manager (HSM, then DFHSM and finally DFSMShsm) was first implemented by IBM on March 31, 1978 for MVS to reduce the cost of data storage, and to simplify the retrieval of data from slower media.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] The user would not need to know where the data was stored and how to get it back; the computer would retrieve the data automatically.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] The only difference to the user was the speed at which data was returned.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] HSM could originally migrate datasets only to disk volumes and virtual volumes on a IBM 3850 Mass Storage Facility, but a later release supported magnetic tape volumes for migration level 2 (ML2).
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] Later, IBM ported HSM to its AIX operating system, and then to other Unix-like operating systems such as Solaris, HP-UX and Linux.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] CSIRO Australia's Division of Computing Research implemented an HSM in its DAD (Drums and Display) operating system with its Document Region in the 1960s, with copies of documents being written to 7-track tape and automatic retrieval upon access to the documents.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] HSM was also implemented on the DEC VAX/VMS systems and the Alpha/VMS systems.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] The first implementation date should be readily determined from the VMS System Implementation Manuals or the VMS Product Description Brochures.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] HSM is often used for deep archival storage of data to be held long term at low cost.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] Automated tape robots can silo large quantities of data efficiently with low power consumption.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] Some HSM software products allow the user to place portions of data files on high-speed disk cache and the rest on tape.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] This is used in applications that stream video over the internet—the initial portion of a video is delivered immediately from disk while a robot finds, mounts and streams the rest of the file to the end user.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] Such a system greatly reduces disk cost for large content provision systems.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] HSM software is today used also for tiering between hard disk drives and flash memory, with flash memory being over 30 times faster than magnetic disks, but disks being considerably cheaper.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] The key factor behind HSM is a data migration policy that controls the file transfers in the system.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] More precisely, the policy decides which tier a file should be stored in, so that the entire storage system can be well-organized and have a shortest response time to requests.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] There are several algorithms realizing this process, such as least recently used replacement (LRU), Size-Temperature Replacement(STP), Heuristic Threshold(STEP) etc.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] In research of recent years, there are also some intelligent policies coming up by using machine learning technologies.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] While tiering solutions and caching may look the same on the surface, the fundamental differences lie in the way the faster storage is utilized and the algorithms used to detect and accelerate frequently accessed data.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] Caching operates by making a copy of frequently accessed blocks of data, and storing the copy in the faster storage device and use this copy instead of the original data source on the slower, high capacity backend storage.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] Every time a storage read occurs, the caching software look to see if a copy of this data already exists on the cache and uses that copy, if available.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] Otherwise, the data is read from the slower, high capacity storage.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] Tiering on the other hand operates very differently.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] Rather than making a *copy* of frequently accessed data into fast storage, tiering *moves* data across tiers, for example, by relocating cold data to low cost, high capacity nearline storage devices.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] The basic idea is, mission-critical and highly accesses or "hot" data is stored in expensive medium such as SSD to take advantage of high I/O performance, while nearline or rarely accessed or "cold" data is stored in nearline storage medium such as HDD and tapes which are inexpensive.
[src:aws-glacier/hierarchical-storage-management] Thus, the "data temperature" or activity levels determines the primary storage hierarchy.
[src:aws-glacier/nearline-storage] Nearline storage dates back to the IBM 3850 Mass Storage System (MSS) tape library, which was announced in 1974.
[src:aws-glacier/nearline-storage] For example, always-on spinning hard disk drives are online storage, while spinning drives that spin down automatically, such as in Massive Arrays of Idle Disks (MAID), are nearline storage.
[src:aws-glacier/nearline-storage] Removable media such as tape cartridges that can be automatically loaded, as in tape libraries, are nearline storage, while tape cartridges that must be manually loaded are offline storage.
[src:aws-glacier/nearline-storage] This process is not instant, but it only requires a few seconds.
[src:aws-glacier/nearline-storage] Nearline tape and optical storage has the advantage of relatively longer lifespans compared to spinning hard drives, simply due to the storage media being idle and usually stored in protected dust-free enclosures when not in use.
[src:aws-glacier/nearline-storage] In a robotic tape loading system, the tape drive used for accessing data experiences the most wear and may need occasional replacement, but the tapes themselves can last for years to decades.
[src:aws-glacier/nearline-storage] If there are sealable access doors between the access mechanism and the media, it is possible for the idle media storage enclosure to survive fire, floods, lightning strikes, and other disasters.
[src:aws-glacier/nearline-storage] MAID (massive array of idle drives) systems archive data in an array of hard disk drives, with most drives in a MAID usually stopped.
[src:aws-glacier/nearline-storage] The MAID system spins up each drive on demand when necessary to read (or in some cases to write) data on that drive.
[src:aws-glacier/nearline-storage] For a given amount of storage capacity, MAID systems have higher densities and lower power and cooling requirements than "hot" storage systems that keep all the disks spinning at full speed at all times.
[src:aws-glacier/nearline-storage] Some hard drive and storage systems vendors and suppliers use the term in reference to low-rotational speed hard drives that are built to be more reliable than generic desktop and laptop computer hard drives.
[src:aws-glacier/nearline-storage] They are intended to be operational continuously for 24 hours a day, seven days a week, possibly for several years.
[src:aws-glacier/nearline-storage] Nearline hard drives may be used in personal or small business network-attached storage (NAS) systems, or as non-critical moderate-performance data storage on servers, where greater durability is required for the drive to operate continuously.
[src:aws-glacier/nearline-storage] By comparison, standard hard drives are assumed to only be in operation for a few hours each day, and are not spinning when the computer is either turned off or in sleep mode.
[src:aws-glacier/nearline-storage] Standard hard drives may also use data caching methods that can improve single-drive performance, but would interfere with the operation of multi-drive RAID storage systems, potentially causing data loss or corruption.
[src:aws-glacier/nearline-storage] Specifically the term *nearline hard drive* is being used to refer to high-capacity Serial ATA drives that work with Serial Attached SCSI storage devices.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] In computer architecture, the **memory hierarchy** separates computer storage into a hierarchy based on response time.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] Since response time, complexity, and capacity are related, the levels may also be distinguished by their performance and controlling technologies.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] Memory hierarchy affects performance in computer architectural design, algorithm predictions, and lower level programming constructs involving locality of reference.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] Designing for high performance requires considering the restrictions of the memory hierarchy, i.e. the size and capabilities of each component.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] Each of the various components can be viewed as part of a hierarchy of memories (*m*1, *m*2, ..., *mn*) in which each member mi is typically smaller and faster than the next highest member *m**i*+1 of the hierarchy.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] To limit waiting by higher levels, a lower level will respond by filling a buffer and then signaling for activating the transfer.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] This is a general memory hierarchy structuring.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] For example, a paging algorithm may be considered as a level for virtual memory when designing a computer architecture, and one can include a level of nearline storage between online and offline storage.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] The number of levels in the memory hierarchy and the performance at each level has increased over time.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] The type of memory or storage components also change historically.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] Some CPUs include additional levels of cache between L3 and memory.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] For example, the Haswell microarchitecture includes an L4 cache of 128 MB on mobile units.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] The lower levels of the hierarchy – from mass storage downwards – are also known as tiered storage.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] For example, always-on spinning disks are online, while spinning disks that spin down, such as massive arrays of idle disk (MAID), are nearline.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] Removable media such as tape cartridges that can be automatically loaded, as in a tape library, are nearline, while cartridges that must be manually loaded are offline.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] Most modern CPUs are so fast that, for most program workloads, the bottleneck is the locality of reference of memory accesses and the efficiency of the caching and memory transfer between different levels of the hierarchy.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] As a result, the CPU spends much of its time idling, waiting for memory I/O to complete.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] This is sometimes called the *space cost*, as a larger memory object is more likely to overflow a small and fast level and require use of a larger, slower level.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] The resulting load on memory use is known as *pressure* (respectively *register pressure*, *cache pressure*, and (main) *memory pressure*).
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] Modern programming languages mainly assume two levels of memory, main (*working*) memory and mass storage.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] The exception is the relatively low-level assembly language and in the inline assemblers of higher-level languages such as C where "prefetch" instructions can be used to preload the cache.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] Many programmers assume one level of memory.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] This works fine until the application hits a performance wall.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] At that point, the programmer needs to change the code's memory access patterns to that it works well with cache resources.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] A classic illustration of the effect of locality and caching is in the form of changing the order of iterating a three-dimensional array.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] *Computer Systems: A Programmer's Perspective* is a classic textbook that deals with this aspect of systems programming.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] Memory tiering is implemented on Linux as an extension to NUMA, where each memory provider has a CPU-less NUMA node with an appropriate "abstract distance" reflecting its performance.
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] The existing scheme for migrating memory between NUMA nodes using "hotness" indicated by page faults is adapted to tiering by Huang Ying (Al Maruf's TPP scheme is not in Linux mainline).
[src:aws-glacier/tiered-storage] It also uses a weighted-interleave allocation policy.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] On ordinary (non-WORM) data storage devices, the number of times data can be modified is limited only by the lifespan of the device, as modification involves physical changes that may cause wear to the device.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] The "read many" aspect is unremarkable, as modern storage devices permit unlimited reading of data once written.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] Historical exceptions include time-limited discs such as Flexplay, designed for short-term rental of movies; and early non-volatile memory technologies such as magnetic-core memory and bubble memory, from which reading data also erased it.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] WORM prevents important data being deleted or modified, helping to preserve its authenticity.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] WORM drives preceded the invention of the CD-R, DVD-R and BD-R.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] These drives typically used either a 5.1 in (13 cm) or a 12 in (30 cm) disc in a cartridge, with an ablative optical layer that could be written to only once, and were often used in places like libraries that needed to store large amounts of data.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] Interfaces to connect these to PCs also existed.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] Punched cards and paper tape are obsolete WORM media.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] Although any unpunched area of the medium could be punched after the first write of the medium, doing so was virtually never useful.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] Read-only memory (ROM) is also a WORM medium.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] Such memory may contain the instructions to a computer to read the operating system from another storage device such as a hard disk.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] The non-technical end-user, however, cannot write the ROM even once but considers it part of the unchangeable computing platform.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] WORM was utilized for broker-dealer records within the Financial Industry Regulatory Authority and the U.S.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] The CD-R, DVD-R and BD-R optical discs for computers are common WORM devices.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] On these discs, no region of the disc can be recorded a second time.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] Through packet writing, which uses the Universal Disk Format (UDF) file system, these discs often use a file system that permits additional files, and even revised versions of a file by the same name, to be recorded in a different region of the disc.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] To the user, the disc appears to allow additions and revisions until all the disk space is used.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] The SD card and microSD card spec allows for multiple forms of write-protection.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] The most common form, only available when using a full-size SD card, provides a physical write protection switch which allows the user to advise the host card reader to disallow write access.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] This does not protect the data on the card if the card reader hardware is not built to respect the write protection switch.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] Multiple vendors beginning in the early 2000s developed magnetic WORM devices.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] These archival grade storage devices utilize a variation of RAID and magnetic storage technologies to secure data from unauthorized alteration or modification at both the hardware and software levels.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] As the cost of magnetic (and solid-state) storage has decreased, so has the cost for these archival storage technologies.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] These technologies are almost always integrated directly into a content/document management system that manages retention schedules and access controls, along with document level history.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] There are multiple vendors providing magnetic storage technologies including NetApp, EMC Centera, KOM Networks, and others.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] In 2013, GreenTec-USA, Inc. developed WORM hard disk drives in capacities of 3 TB and greater.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] Prevention of rewrite is done at the physical disk level and cannot be modified or overridden by the attached computer.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] In the first decade of the 21st century, there had been a renewed interest in WORM based on organic components, such as PEDOT:PSS or other polymers such as PVK or PCz.
[src:aws-glacier/write-once-read-many] Organic WORM devices, considered organic memory, can be used as memory elements for low-power RFID tags.
